{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"HTML Accessibility (ARIA)","slug":"html-accessibility","subject":"HTML","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"15 minutes","prerequisites":["HTML Semantic Elements"],"learning_objectives":["Understand Web Accessibility (a11y)","Learn about Screen Readers","Introduction to WAI-ARIA (roles, states, properties)","Use aria-label and aria-hidden"],"theory":"# HTML Accessibility (ARIA Check)\n\nWeb Accessibility (**a11y**) ensures that websites are usable by people with disabilities (blindness, low vision, motor impairments).\n\n## Semantic HTML is King\nThe best way to ensure accessibility is to use **Semantic HTML** (`<button>`, `<nav>`, `<label>`). Standard elements have built-in accessibility features.\n\n## What is ARIA?\nIf standard HTML isn't enough (e.g., custom widgets like popups), we use **WAI-ARIA** (Web Accessibility Initiative - Accessible Rich Internet Applications).\n\nARIA attributes do NOT change functionality or style; they only describe the element to assistive technology (Screen Readers).\n\n## Common ARIA Attributes\n\n### 1. `aria-label`\nProvides a label for an element that has no visible text.\n```html\n<button aria-label=\"Close Menu\">X</button>\n```\n\n### 2. `role`\nDefines the role of an element.\n```html\n<div role=\"alert\">Error detected!</div>\n```\n\n### 3. `aria-hidden`\nHides an element from screen readers (but keeps it visible).\n```html\n<span aria-hidden=\"true\">Decorative Icon</span>\n```\n\n### 4. `aria-expanded`\nIndicates if a menu/accordion is open or closed.\n```html\n<button aria-expanded=\"false\">Menu</button>\n```","syntax":"<tag aria-attribute=\"value\">","examples":[{"code":"<button onclick=\"closeDialog()\" aria-label=\"Close\">\n  <i class=\"icon-close\"></i>\n</button>","output":"A button with an icon.","explanation":"A screen reader would just say 'Button' without the label. With aria-label, it says 'Close Button'."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Overusing ARIA","correction":"First rule of ARIA: Don't use ARIA. Use standard HTML elements whenever possible.","example":"‚ùå <div role=\"button\" onclick=\"...\">Click</div>\n‚úÖ <button onclick=\"...\">Click</button>"},{"mistake":"Forgetting alt text","correction":"Images need alt text. ARIA doesn't replace basic HTML requirements.","example":"Use alt=\"...\""}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"What is the first rule of ARIA?","difficulty":"Intermediate","answer":"The first rule of ARIA is: If you can use a native HTML element (like <button> or <input>) instead of a custom element with ARIA, do so."},{"question":"What is aria-label used for?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"It provides a text label for screen readers when an element doesn't have visible text (like an icon-only button)."}],"practice_problems":[{"difficulty":"Intermediate","problem":"Make a decorative <div> containing an icon invisible to screen readers.","hint":"Use aria-hidden.","solution":"<div aria-hidden=\"true\">üé®</div>"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"Custom Dropdowns","description":"When building a custom React/Vue dropdown, you MUST use aria-expanded and aria-haspopup to tell blind users that a menu has appeared.","code":"aria-expanded=\"true\""}],"exam_notes":["Native HTML > ARIA","ARIA adds semantics, not behavior","aria-label for textless controls","aria-hidden to hide decoration","role='...' defines purpose"],"summary":"Accessibility is a right, not a feature. While semantic HTML gets you 90% of the way there, ARIA attributes help bridge the gap for complex, dynamic interfaces, ensuring everyone can use your website.","order":32},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"html-document-structure","path":"content/html/html-document-structure.json","title":"HTML Document Structure","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"html-comments","path":"content/html/html-comments.json","title":"HTML Comments","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML",